</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[653,742,1365,1391]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[653,742,1365,1391]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blote" authorityYear="1931" box="[756,962,1364,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parviceps" subGenus="Neophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[756,787,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[811,830,1365,1390]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[853,962,1365,1390]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">parviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergroth" authorityYear="1894" box="[1023,1274,1364,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadriguttata" subGenus="Neophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[1023,1054,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1078,1097,1365,1390]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1120,1274,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">quadriguttata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,392,2039]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">
Species of the subgenera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[486,610,1400,1426]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[486,610,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[618,677,1401,1427]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahmad &amp; Abbas" authorityYear="1987" box="[732,898,1400,1426]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="478" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Neophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[732,898,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Neophysopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have sexual dimorphism in the swelling degree of the calli, the width of the femur, and the curvature of the protibia (
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik, J. L." box="[950,1101,1436,1463]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="505 - 584" refId="ref24490" refString="Stehlik, J. L. (2013) Review and reclassification of the Old World genus Physopelta (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Largidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 53 (2), 505 - 584." type="journal article" year="2013">Stehlík 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Sexual dimorphism is more distinct in larger male than in smaller male (
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik, J. L." box="[645,794,1472,1499]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="115 - 129" refId="ref24456" refString="Stehlik, J. L. (2007) Largidae and Pyrrhocoridae (Heteroptera) of Meghalaya state, India. Acta Musei Moraviae, Scientiae Biologicae, 92, 115 - 129." type="journal article" year="2007">Stehlík 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,392,2039]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[199,323,1508,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,323,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species were diagnosed by previous authors based on the differences in the morphological characteristics such as body shape, size of the compound eye, shape of the antenna, and the presence or absence of the procoxal projection and protrochanteral wrinkles (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Stal, C." box="[762,871,1580,1607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="390 - 404" refId="ref24358" refString="Stal, C. (1863) Beitrag zur Kentniss des Pyrrhocoriden. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift, 7, 390 - 404. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / mmnd. 47918630307" type="journal article" year="1863">Stål 1863</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Blote, H. C." box="[883,1009,1580,1607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="97 - 117" refId="ref21700" refString="Blote, H. C. (1931) Catalogue of the Pyrrhocoridae in ' s Rijks Museum van Natuurlijke Historie. Zoologische Mededeelingen, Leiden, 14, 97 - 117." type="journal article" year="1931">Blöte 1931</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Redei, D. &amp; Tsai, J. - F. &amp; Yang, M. - M." box="[1021,1215,1580,1607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" refId="ref24020" refString="Redei, D., Tsai, J. - F. &amp; Yang, M. - M. (2009) Heteropteran Fauna of Taiwan: Cotton stainers and relatives (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Pyrrhocoroidea). National Chung Hsing University, Taichung, 52 pp." type="book" year="2009">
Rédei 
<emphasis box="[1093,1142,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">et al</emphasis>
. 2009
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kohno, K. &amp; Hayashi, M. &amp; Miyamoto, S." box="[1227,1432,1580,1607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="90 - 91" refId="ref22979" refString="Kohno, K., Hayashi, M. &amp; Miyamoto, S. (2012) Family Largidae Amyot &amp; Serville, 1843. In: Ishikawa, T., Takai, M. &amp; Yasunaga, T. (Eds.), A field guide to Japanese bugs. Terrestrial heteropterans III. Zenkoku Noson Kyoiku Kyokai, Publishing Co., Ltd., Tokyo, pp. 399 - 402, pls. 90 - 91. [in Japanese]" type="book chapter" year="2012">
Kohno 
<emphasis box="[1310,1359,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik, J. L." box="[151,301,1616,1643]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="505 - 584" refId="ref24490" refString="Stehlik, J. L. (2013) Review and reclassification of the Old World genus Physopelta (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Largidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 53 (2), 505 - 584." type="journal article" year="2013">Stehlík 2013</bibRefCitation>
). These characteristics are also useful for the identification of the new species described below. In addition, the structure of male and female terminalia provide good characters for identification among at least the eastern Asian species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,392,2039]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">
An apparatus consisting of a projection of procoxa and wrinkles of the protrochanter has been named “stridulatory organ” by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stehlik, J. L." box="[324,490,1760,1787]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" pagination="505 - 584" refId="ref24490" refString="Stehlik, J. L. (2013) Review and reclassification of the Old World genus Physopelta (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Largidae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 53 (2), 505 - 584." type="journal article" year="2013">Stehlík (2013)</bibRefCitation>
; however, the stridulatory behavior of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[930,1054,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[930,1054,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species has not been observed so far. Also, the procoxal projection on procoxa in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blote" authorityYear="1931" box="[694,901,1796,1823]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parviceps" subGenus="Neophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[694,725,1796,1822]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[749,768,1797,1822]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[792,901,1797,1822]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">parviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is present in macropterous morph but is absent in brachypterous morph, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Souma &amp; Ishikawa, 2021" authorityName="Souma &amp; Ishikawa" authorityYear="2021" box="[484,708,1832,1859]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutaspidata" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Neophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[484,515,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[539,558,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[582,708,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">lutaspidata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[716,806,1833,1859]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[716,806,1833,1859]" pageId="2" pageNumber="463" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has only the wrinkles in the protrochanter. Therefore, a horn-shaped projection of procoxa and wrinkles of the protrochanter are here renamed as procoxal projection and protrochanteral wrinkles, respectively.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,392,2039]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,150,393]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="464" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">
The antennomeral oligomery is confirmed in 
<taxonomicName authority="gutta" authorityName="gutta (Burmeister" authorityYear="1834" box="[705,923,1940,1967]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="gutta" subGenus="Neophysopelta" subSpecies="gutta">
<emphasis box="[705,736,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[759,778,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[801,923,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">gutta gutta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[938,1024,1940,1967]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1492,1516]" captionTargetBox="[154,1430,425,1465]" captionTargetId="figure-130@3.[151,1436,417,1468]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus images of four Physopelta (Neophysopelta) species, dorsal view: Ph. (N.) gutta gutta, male (A) and female (B) from Japan proper; Ph. (N.) fusciscutellata sp. nov., male from the main island of Taiwan (C) and female from the Ryukyu Islands, Japan (D); Ph. (N.) quadriguttata, male (E, G) and female (F) from the main island of Taiwan; Ph. (N.) lutaspidata sp. nov., male from the main island of Taiwan (H). Arrows mark antenna with antennomeral oligomery and malformed calli. Scale bar: 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4668176" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4668176/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blote" authorityYear="1931" box="[1087,1291,1940,1967]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parviceps" subGenus="Neophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[1087,1118,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1141,1160,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1182,1291,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">parviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1306,1423,1940,1967]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1143,1167]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,184,1113]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1436,181,1119]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus images of Physopelta (Neophysopelta) parviceps, dorsal view: macropterous male (A) and female (B) from Japan proper; macropterous male (C, E) and female (D, F) from the Ryukyu Islands, Japan; brachypterous male (G) and female (H) from Japan proper. Arrows mark antennae with antennomeral oligomery. Scale bar: 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4668179" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4668179/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="463">Fig. 2B, F</figureCitation>
). These three individuals lack antennomere III. Similar teratological forms are known in Cimicomorpha Leston, Pendergrast &amp; Southwood, 1954, Gerromorpha Popov, 1971, Leptopodomorpha Popov, 1971, and Pentatomomorpha (
<bibRefCitation author="Leston, D." box="[159,302,150,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" pagination="890" refId="ref23396" refString="Leston, D. (1952). Antennal oligomery in Heteroptera. Nature, 169, 890. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / 169890 a 0" type="journal article" year="1952">Leston 1952</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Stusak, J. M. &amp; Stehlik, J. L." box="[314,568,151,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" pagination="89 - 105" refId="ref24617" refString="Stusak, J. M. &amp; Stehlik, J. L. (1978) Second contribution to the teratology of Tingidae (Heteroptera) Antennal anomalies. Acta Musei Moraviae. Scientiae Biologicae, 63, 89 - 105." type="journal article" year="1978">Štusák &amp; Stehlík 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T." box="[578,751,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" pagination="55 - 58" refId="ref25740" refString="Yasunaga, T. (2018) Teratological forms found in two Japanese heteropterans (Heteroptera: Gerridae and Miridae). Rostria, 62, 55 - 58." type="journal article" year="2018">Yasunaga 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Taszakowski, A. &amp; Kaszyca-Taszakowska, N." box="[762,1260,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" pagination="1027" refId="ref24699" refString="Taszakowski, A. &amp; Kaszyca-Taszakowska, N. (2020) Teratological cases of the antennae in the family Aradidae (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Scientific Reports, 10, 1027. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / s 41598 - 020 - 57891 - 1" type="journal article" year="2020">Taszakowski &amp; Kaszyca-Taszakowska 2020</bibRefCitation>
, etc.). Thus, the antennomeral oligomery may be common in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[720,844,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[720,844,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species as other heteropterans.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,150,393]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">
Although only dozens of individuals are found on their host plants at noon, hundreds of individuals of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are sometimes attracted to artificial light at night (
<figureCitation box="[855,938,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1926,1950]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,1183,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-184@25.[154,1433,1183,1902]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 17. A number of individuals of Physopelta (Neophysopelta) quadriguttata from the main island of Taiwan attracted to artificial light." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4668213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4668213/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
). On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName authority="gutta" authorityName="gutta (Burmeister" authorityYear="1834" box="[1170,1387,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="gutta" subGenus="Neophysopelta" subSpecies="gutta">
<emphasis box="[1170,1201,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">Ph</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[1224,1243,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">N</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[1265,1387,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">gutta gutta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected from a volcanic island, whose flora does not include its host plants, 
<taxonomicName box="[1033,1250,295,321]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Osmeridae" genus="Mallotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Osmeriformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis box="[1033,1250,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">Mallotus japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.f.) Müll.Arg. (
<taxonomicName box="[159,329,331,358]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Euphorbiaceae</taxonomicName>
) and its close relatives (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ohba, H." box="[648,777,331,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" pagination="273 - 286" refId="ref23953" refString="Ohba, H. (1989) Euphorbiaceae. In: Satake, Y., Hara, H., Watari, S. &amp; Tominari, T. (Eds.), Wild flowers of Japan, woody plants. Vol. 1. Heibonsha, Tokyo, pp. 257 - 271, pls. 273 - 286. [in Japanese]" type="book chapter" year="1989">Ohba 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Komatsu, T. &amp; Kunikane, N. &amp; Imoto N." box="[791,1029,331,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" pagination="79 - 83" refId="ref23140" refString="Komatsu, T., Kunikane, N. &amp; Imoto N. (2009) [Insecta from Oshima-Oshima Island, Hokkaido, Japan]. Jezoensis, 35, 79 - 83. [in Japanese]" type="journal article" year="2009">
Komatsu 
<emphasis box="[901,952,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">et al</emphasis>
. 2009
</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, some species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[1312,1436,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="464">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to have strong phototaxis and flight ability.
</paragraph>
